      {
        "number": 6,
        "title": "The mystery, the trumpet, and the victory that funds labor",
        "range": "15:50-58",
        "excerpt": "Behold, I tell you a mystery; we will not all sleep, but we will all be changed, in a moment, in the twinkling of an eye, at the last trumpet... Therefore, my beloved brethren, be steadfast, immovable, always abounding in the work of the Lord.",
        "body": "Paul closes with apocalyptic disclosure and pastoral charge. Verse 50 states the basic incompatibility: *flesh and blood cannot inherit the kingdom of God; nor does the perishable inherit the imperishable.* The present mode of embodiment is structurally unfit for the eschatological kingdom. Transformation is necessary — not annihilation of the body, but the transformation Paul has been describing.\n\n*Behold, I tell you a mystery* (*musterion*, v. 51) — apocalyptic disclosure formula. A *mystery* in Paul is not a riddle but a previously hidden truth now revealed (cf. Ephesians 3:3-6). The revelation: *we will not all sleep, but we will all be changed.* Some believers will be alive at Christ's coming; for them, transformation will be instantaneous — they will skip the dying-and-rising sequence and be transformed directly. This is one of the NT's clearest texts on what later theology called the rapture or translation of the living saints (cf. 1 Thessalonians 4:15-17).\n\nThe transformation is *in a moment, in the twinkling of an eye, at the last trumpet*. *Atomos* (moment) literally means *indivisible* — the smallest possible unit of time. *Rhipe ophthalmou* (twinkling of an eye) is the blink, perhaps the fastest physiological event humans can perceive. The transformation is not a process but an instant. *The trumpet will sound, and the dead will be raised imperishable, and we will be changed.* The trumpet evokes Sinai (Exodus 19:16), the Day of the Lord (Joel 2:1; Zephaniah 1:16), and Christ's own teaching (Matthew 24:31). At the final trumpet, both the dead and the living are transformed simultaneously.\n\nVerse 53 uses the clothing metaphor: *this perishable must put on the imperishable, and this mortal must put on immortality.* The verb *enduo* (put on) — used elsewhere of putting on Christ (Romans 13:14), the new self (Ephesians 4:24), the armor of God (Ephesians 6:11) — pictures imperishability as a garment overlaying the present body. Continuity is preserved (*this* perishable, *this* mortal); transformation is added.\n\nThen the prophetic crescendo. *Death is swallowed up in victory* — Isaiah 25:8 LXX. *O death, where is your victory? O death, where is your sting?* — Hosea 13:14 LXX. Death is mocked as a conquered foe; what once held the world in terror now has no sting. Verse 56 explains the metaphor's anatomy: *the sting of death is sin, and the power of sin is the law.* Death stings because sin makes it lethal (Romans 6:23); sin has power because the law exposes and condemns it (Romans 7:7-13). But Christ has dealt with both — bearing sin (15:3) and fulfilling the law — so death's apparatus is dismantled. *But thanks be to God, who gives us the victory through our Lord Jesus Christ* (v. 57). The chapter's doxological climax — *charis* (thanks/grace) and *nikos* (victory) converge in Jesus.\n\nThe terminal *therefore* of v. 58 carries all 57 prior verses. *Be steadfast* (*hedraios* — seated, settled, immovable in conviction). *Immovable* (*ametakinetos* — not to be shifted off the foundation). *Always abounding in the work of the Lord* (*perisseuo* — overflowing). *Knowing that your toil is not in vain in the Lord* (*ouk... kenos* — not empty, in deliberate echo of the *kenos* of v. 14). The chapter that began with the threat of empty preaching and empty faith ends with the promise of not-empty labor. Resurrection grounds work. Because the body will be raised, what you do in the body matters and abides.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Musterion* (v. 51) — revealed truth, not enigma. *Atomos* (v. 52) — the indivisible instant; the Greek word from which English *atom* derives, here used temporally not physically. *Salpinx* (trumpet) and *salpizo* (sound the trumpet) evoke Sinai theophany. *Enduo* (vv. 53-54) — put on as clothing; the resurrection state is *put on* over the present self. *Kenos* in v. 58 deliberately reverses the *kenos* of v. 14 — Christianity's labor is not, in fact, empty. *Hedraios* and *ametakinetos* are the architectural vocabulary of foundational stability."
      }
